1
00:00:01,465 --> 00:00:02,726
Greetings and good evening.

2
00:00:02,766 --> 00:00:05,589
I trust you've had a fruitful day.

3
00:00:05,649 --> 00:00:09,212
I do not say happy, though I hope it has been happy.

4
00:00:10,353 --> 00:00:26,410
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodassa

5
00:00:27,082 --> 00:00:39,639
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed noble and self-awakened one.

6
00:00:42,343 --> 00:00:45,628
I just want to... Let me see if I can just drop this down a bit.

7
00:00:46,328 --> 00:00:56,902
I just want to read an email that came through.

8
00:00:56,984 --> 00:01:04,953
They say, well, they thank me for the live stream.

9
00:01:05,713 --> 00:01:10,459
I have been meditating with you daily and have set up my evenings around this time.

10
00:01:11,540 --> 00:01:14,644
You won't be surprised by this, but it's changed my life.

11
00:01:15,325 --> 00:01:18,608
I'm sleeping better, feel less burdened in the day.

12
00:01:19,569 --> 00:01:25,876
During meditation, I'm able to stay with painful surface and deeper emotions whilst holding them with metta.

13
00:01:26,549 --> 00:01:34,260
Seeing you meditate and knowing lots of others are doing the same at the same time offers a sense of connection and commitment to my practice.

14
00:01:34,480 --> 00:01:34,900
Thank you.

15
00:01:35,561 --> 00:01:36,263
There we are.

16
00:01:39,087 --> 00:01:39,828
Thank you so much.

17
00:01:41,129 --> 00:01:43,111
So a little bit of feedback there.

18
00:01:43,373 --> 00:01:48,039
I am presuming that that's the same for everybody.

19
00:01:48,620 --> 00:01:49,581
Oh, just a minute.

20
00:01:49,921 --> 00:01:51,403
I won't be back in a second.

21
00:01:51,743 --> 00:01:52,986
I'm going to forget my notes again.

22
00:01:53,186 --> 00:01:53,686
Excuse me.

23
00:02:26,995 --> 00:02:27,975
Just put it down to age.

24
00:02:30,159 --> 00:02:35,347
Now, I just want to go back, just try to complete a little bit of this Eighth Bonobo Path.

25
00:02:35,967 --> 00:02:49,848
Remember that my aim over this two months or more, let's hope it's just two months, was to introduce you to the various discourses in the Middle End sayings.

26
00:02:50,449 --> 00:02:55,736
So I'll try to get through most of this this evening.

27
00:02:56,138 --> 00:03:09,811
So remember, we started with Samaditti, right understanding, the Eightfold Path, the Eightfold Path which is transcendental, not in between indulgence and aversion, but rising above it.

28
00:03:09,971 --> 00:03:12,894
In that sense, it's the middle, it's transcendent.

29
00:03:13,715 --> 00:03:24,745
And remember that this Samaditti is to do with conceptual, the way we conceive, the way we look at things and experience things through our concepts.

30
00:03:25,400 --> 00:03:38,461
And the big mistake, according to the Buddha, is to seek any sort of lasting happiness in anything to do with this world, that things are impermanent, radically so.

31
00:03:38,661 --> 00:03:41,605
They're arising and passing away momentarily.

32
00:03:41,626 --> 00:03:49,137
And that this whole concept of me, the self, is causing a great deal of problems.

33
00:03:49,677 --> 00:03:52,081
And that manifests through our attachments.

34
00:03:53,429 --> 00:03:56,432
Attachments are psychological dependencies.

35
00:03:57,054 --> 00:04:00,938
We use things, we use people in order to make ourselves feel happy.

36
00:04:01,400 --> 00:04:06,447
That's not the same as metta, compassion and generosity.

37
00:04:06,526 --> 00:04:12,194
That's coming from a different place, coming from the place of wisdom, coming from the place of not me, me, me.

38
00:04:14,478 --> 00:04:22,069
And this conceptual, the right concept draws us into these social virtues.

39
00:04:22,336 --> 00:04:32,309
the main ones being generosity, love, goodwill, and compassion, the desire to help people.

40
00:04:33,451 --> 00:04:46,047
Now, once this is passed into our attitudes, into our intentions, then of course they begin to manifest in the way we think, which is an internal speech, an internal speaking.

41
00:04:46,067 --> 00:04:46,867
I speak to myself.

42
00:04:47,569 --> 00:04:49,591
Sometimes I'm speaking to myself, but also

43
00:04:49,841 --> 00:04:54,927
I find myself speaking to lots of other people too inside this little head of mine.

44
00:04:55,848 --> 00:05:00,473
And it includes, of course, speech in ordinary daily life.

45
00:05:01,233 --> 00:05:07,199
And the type of speech we don't want to get into is, of course, untruths.

46
00:05:07,279 --> 00:05:09,101
We don't want to do that.

47
00:05:09,401 --> 00:05:11,064
We don't want to slander people.

48
00:05:14,408 --> 00:05:19,612
Blake says, a truth told with bad intent beats all the lies you can invent.

49
00:05:19,862 --> 00:05:22,925
So that's a beautiful little verse.

50
00:05:24,288 --> 00:05:36,079
It depends on your intention, which makes it either slander or having to say something which might undermine somebody's reputation, but it might be for good reason.

51
00:05:38,944 --> 00:05:47,692
Abusive speech, using speech in order to upset people, you know.

52
00:05:48,685 --> 00:05:54,490
And finally, just chit chat, you know, just talking for talking sake, just a waste of time, really.

53
00:05:54,511 --> 00:06:06,262
And that, you know, we hate silence when you're walking with a friend or walking with somebody who's close to your partner or a child, you know, there's always this compulsion to have to communicate.

54
00:06:06,302 --> 00:06:07,423
You have to speak.

55
00:06:08,023 --> 00:06:12,588
And it's a sign of maturity of a relationship that you can, you can be silent with each other.

56
00:06:12,608 --> 00:06:17,291
I mean, that's, that's my understanding anyway.

57
00:06:18,300 --> 00:06:34,300
So when it comes to free speech, there was a period there a couple of years back or somewhere where free speech came up around this whole business of Islam and not insulting the prophets.

58
00:06:34,401 --> 00:06:35,523
And if you remember all that.

59
00:06:35,562 --> 00:06:35,742
Yeah.

60
00:06:36,444 --> 00:06:39,406
And there came this phrase, the right to insult.

61
00:06:40,148 --> 00:06:43,853
And that's a very aggressive way of saying that.

62
00:06:44,086 --> 00:06:48,730
Everybody has a right to express their opinion, even though they know it'll upset somebody.

63
00:06:49,471 --> 00:06:51,533
But it became very hard.

64
00:06:51,894 --> 00:06:54,958
It became a sort of aggressive thing, the right to insult.

65
00:06:55,579 --> 00:06:57,380
I don't think you have a right to insult.

66
00:06:58,101 --> 00:07:05,971
You have a right to express yourself, your own truths, even though it might upset somebody.

67
00:07:06,672 --> 00:07:07,932
And we normally...

68
00:07:08,115 --> 00:07:10,920
When that happens, we normally introduce it, don't we?

69
00:07:10,939 --> 00:07:12,302
We say, I know this is going to upset you.

70
00:07:12,382 --> 00:07:15,206
I hope you don't mind, and so on and so forth.

71
00:07:15,225 --> 00:07:17,649
So it's a case of being kind, being gentle.

72
00:07:17,730 --> 00:07:30,389
That's one of the qualities of right speech, being gentle and being truthful, of course, truthful to ourselves, truthful to the situation, and the sense of being beneficial.

73
00:07:31,529 --> 00:07:35,997
You're speaking for either your own benefit, somebody else's benefit,

74
00:07:36,365 --> 00:07:38,427
or your own and somebody else's benefit.

75
00:07:39,528 --> 00:07:44,814
And with a heart of loving kindness, the Buddha says, coming from a heart of loving kindness.

76
00:07:46,154 --> 00:07:56,326
Sometimes that's difficult, of course, when you're talking to somebody who's being aggressive and whatnot, in which case at least you can come from the heart of no harm.

77
00:07:57,687 --> 00:08:01,250
There's no point in upsetting ourselves and getting angry ourselves.

78
00:08:01,591 --> 00:08:03,233
That's just a waste of energy, you know.

79
00:08:03,786 --> 00:08:07,911
And it's that distinction between being aggressive and being assertive.

80
00:08:07,932 --> 00:08:19,086
That's a very clear way of putting it, you know, that you can actually state your truth coming from a position of strength, a position of goodwill, a position of compassion.

81
00:08:20,108 --> 00:08:21,569
You don't have to come from anger.

82
00:08:21,589 --> 00:08:27,877
In fact, if anything, anger manifests a certain weakness because sitting underneath anger, there's always fear.

83
00:08:28,338 --> 00:08:30,802
You don't get angry unless you're afraid.

84
00:08:30,882 --> 00:08:32,244
It's underneath it.

85
00:08:32,344 --> 00:08:33,404
It's underpinning the fear.

86
00:08:33,740 --> 00:08:35,802
The fear, the anger.

87
00:08:36,082 --> 00:08:38,826
Fear is underpinning anger.

88
00:08:41,350 --> 00:08:47,958
And one of the interesting things the Buddha says, of course, to say at the right time, you know, to choose your time to say things.

89
00:08:48,519 --> 00:08:50,121
There's a right time and a wrong time.

90
00:08:50,182 --> 00:08:53,647
And I'm sure we've all experienced dropping a clanger.

91
00:08:54,148 --> 00:09:00,777
So it's a case of recognizing a situation and being careful about what we say.

92
00:09:01,245 --> 00:09:07,371
And I think the key to that when we're with people is the ability to listen.

93
00:09:08,393 --> 00:09:21,746
And I think we find listening difficult, especially when somebody is expressing ideas or positions which are not the same as ours, even opposed to ours.

94
00:09:22,346 --> 00:09:27,793
Then there's a sort of fear, I think, that we're going to be converted, that if they

95
00:09:27,942 --> 00:09:35,808
if we allow ourselves to listen, open-hearted, open-minded, there's this terrible danger that they might change me.

96
00:09:37,971 --> 00:09:51,182
But if we come from that sense of inner stability, just that calmness, just that calmness, and with a willingness to understand the world that they are living in.

97
00:09:51,202 --> 00:09:55,586
I mean, we're all creating our own little worlds, and the intention is,

98
00:09:55,836 --> 00:09:57,940
to understand, well, where are they coming from?

99
00:09:58,159 --> 00:09:59,280
Where are they coming from?

100
00:09:59,301 --> 00:10:01,082
You see, it doesn't have to convert us.

101
00:10:01,464 --> 00:10:10,975
But on the other hand, we may find ourselves that our views and opinions are nuanced by what other people say.

102
00:10:11,375 --> 00:10:12,297
Yeah.

103
00:10:12,456 --> 00:10:15,019
And that's coming from the heart of humility.

104
00:10:15,059 --> 00:10:18,484
You know, none of this business of I'm right and everybody else is wrong.

105
00:10:18,644 --> 00:10:19,806
You know, I'm special that way.

106
00:10:20,787 --> 00:10:25,152
So there's a whole area of right speech, which we can

107
00:10:25,469 --> 00:10:27,532
contact on a daily basis.

108
00:10:28,173 --> 00:10:48,443
And that would be the purpose of an evening reflection, a evening reflection where you look back and you've had a conversation with somebody that didn't go right, or you had a conversation with somebody where it really did go right, where you felt you were skillful, wise, and stuff like that.

109
00:10:49,065 --> 00:10:52,910
And on both counts, you can reinforce, you can encourage us

110
00:10:53,092 --> 00:10:54,654
You can congratulate yourself.

111
00:10:54,674 --> 00:10:55,876
There's nothing wrong with that, you know.

112
00:10:56,677 --> 00:10:57,118
Well done.

113
00:10:57,298 --> 00:10:58,200
Well done, Bodhidharma.

114
00:10:58,360 --> 00:10:59,761
Yeah, absolutely.

115
00:10:59,782 --> 00:11:06,009
And if you haven't done so well, you can always encourage yourself, you know, go do better now.

116
00:11:06,029 --> 00:11:08,013
Go do better than that.

117
00:11:08,033 --> 00:11:10,475
So there's no need to get angry with oneself, hate oneself.

118
00:11:10,495 --> 00:11:12,778
It's a waste, a complete waste of energy, useless.

119
00:11:13,659 --> 00:11:17,885
It doesn't go anywhere at all except to more misery, just creates more misery for us.

120
00:11:20,363 --> 00:11:22,606
So that's the position of right speech.

121
00:11:23,347 --> 00:11:29,859
And again, it's coming from these attitudes that we've developed because of our different view about life.

122
00:11:29,879 --> 00:11:31,160
See, it all goes back to view.

123
00:11:31,441 --> 00:11:34,005
And this is what I meant about they're all important.

124
00:11:34,225 --> 00:11:36,470
And we'll see why when I come to the end.

125
00:11:37,951 --> 00:11:39,634
But some precede others.

126
00:11:39,815 --> 00:11:40,937
Some precede others.

127
00:11:43,582 --> 00:11:52,451
When it comes to samakamanta, which is right action, that's usually expressed as the moral law, just basic morality.

128
00:11:53,332 --> 00:11:58,076
You know, not to kill, steal, offensive sexual behavior, conduct.

129
00:11:58,918 --> 00:12:06,446
And, well, there's including in this being untruth.

130
00:12:06,466 --> 00:12:12,932
And, of course, the use of drugs and alcohol and stuff, which isn't very good for us.

131
00:12:15,764 --> 00:12:43,071
and uh the move there is is towards refinement it's towards refinement so where obviously we've given up killing at least for a while and then uh and we're moving towards protecting protecting uh each other protecting animals protecting the wildlife except protecting flowers you know it's all so it's a change of attitude uh and protection

132
00:12:43,253 --> 00:12:45,956
Stealing moves us towards generosity.

133
00:12:46,658 --> 00:13:00,097
Offensive sexual conduct moves us towards right relationship, you know, treating the other as a person, not as an object to satisfy our personal erotic desires.

134
00:13:03,243 --> 00:13:05,846
When it comes to right speech, well, we've done that, of course.

135
00:13:05,986 --> 00:13:12,736
And this idea of non-alcohol, which is very difficult for our society because we are alcohol-based, you know.

136
00:13:13,291 --> 00:13:22,543
And it's a case of recognizing that under the influence, especially if we've drunk a little bit too much, we can do things which aren't particularly good.

137
00:13:24,946 --> 00:13:36,341
And when you consider that our purpose is to maintain a sort of bright awareness at all times, as soon as you wake up to the point you fall asleep, we're supposed to be bright.

138
00:13:36,361 --> 00:13:37,523
We're supposed to be mindful.

139
00:13:37,702 --> 00:13:39,365
Yeah.

140
00:13:39,385 --> 00:13:42,048
Putting alcohol in the system really doesn't help.

141
00:13:42,754 --> 00:13:45,318
I had a very good experience with that myself.

142
00:13:46,419 --> 00:13:51,567
I'd given up alcohol and I'd come out of a Zen session.

143
00:13:51,587 --> 00:13:53,850
So I was going right back to the beginning of my practice.

144
00:13:54,692 --> 00:14:01,923
And just on the way home, I sort of slipped into a pub and had half a beer, half a mild or something.

145
00:14:02,724 --> 00:14:06,009
And I did it in order to see what effect it would have.

146
00:14:06,809 --> 00:14:11,817
And to my surprise, after I'd drunk it for a little while,

147
00:14:11,999 --> 00:14:14,722
I just felt this sort of curtain.

148
00:14:15,323 --> 00:14:21,592
It's difficult to describe, a sort of net coming down, an actual physical feeling in my brain.

149
00:14:22,975 --> 00:14:26,460
And that convinced me that I had to give it up, which I did.

150
00:14:26,879 --> 00:14:27,100
I did.

151
00:14:28,381 --> 00:14:34,610
So when you consider that poison, I mean, this is the point, isn't it?

152
00:14:34,892 --> 00:14:38,537
That alcohol is the most vicious of poisons for the body.

153
00:14:38,576 --> 00:14:39,999
I mean, it kills brain cells.

154
00:14:40,038 --> 00:14:40,099
It

155
00:14:40,298 --> 00:14:41,458
messes your liver up.

156
00:14:41,479 --> 00:14:42,700
It does all sorts of bad things.

157
00:14:43,520 --> 00:14:46,744
And non-alcoholic beer is very good.

158
00:14:47,144 --> 00:14:51,168
So there's no reason for drinking alcohol at all.

159
00:14:52,328 --> 00:15:06,643
So those are the sort of things we're moving towards, moving towards refinement.

160
00:15:06,909 --> 00:15:10,374
The other thing in that is to do with restraint of the senses.

161
00:15:10,695 --> 00:15:26,014
That's one of the big teachings of the Buddha, to restrain, to guard the senses, to be on the lookout for when the senses do get involved in stuff and to be aware of that reaction that we have to what we see, to what we hear.

162
00:15:28,216 --> 00:15:29,318
Yeah.

163
00:15:29,339 --> 00:15:30,620
Restraining the senses.

164
00:15:32,863 --> 00:15:35,787
I mean, that sounds like suppressing something.

165
00:15:36,289 --> 00:15:36,870
But it's not.

166
00:15:36,951 --> 00:15:42,938
It's sort of holding and saying, no, we don't want to keep developing that particular mental state.

167
00:15:44,500 --> 00:15:56,758
So, like, for instance, when you see something which draws a certain anger out of you or draws a certain neurotic feeling out of you, to actually catch at the beginning and just say, no, you don't want to go there.

168
00:15:58,880 --> 00:16:03,647
And that way you're undermining an old habit, undermining an old habit.

169
00:16:05,720 --> 00:16:11,847
I'm not saying, by the way, that there aren't times when erotic feelings are to the point.

170
00:16:12,067 --> 00:16:14,971
You know, that's within a proper relationship.

171
00:16:17,634 --> 00:16:18,556
Right, livelihood.

172
00:16:18,596 --> 00:16:27,187
Now, the importance of livelihood is an expression of our desire, of the way we see ourselves.

173
00:16:29,629 --> 00:16:35,236
If you happen to have the job that you wanted, if you happen to have the area of work that you wanted,

174
00:16:35,452 --> 00:16:45,264
You want your own personal interest, your own personal bent, your own personal special qualities.

175
00:16:45,765 --> 00:16:50,871
So people want to move towards helping other people.

176
00:16:50,932 --> 00:16:59,543
So they end up being nurses or doctors or involved in some sort of hospital medical staff.

177
00:16:59,562 --> 00:17:04,869
But even wanting to be involved in a hospital as a cleaner, that might be it.

178
00:17:05,051 --> 00:17:09,057
that desire to be involved in that sort of place of helping people.

179
00:17:09,637 --> 00:17:13,863
Other people want to develop their lives to art, you know, or to nature.

180
00:17:13,883 --> 00:17:17,606
Um, they want to be involved in gardens and things like that.

181
00:17:17,646 --> 00:17:26,897
Other people want to be involved in, in artificial intelligence and, and, um, and, uh, information technology and all that sort of stuff.

182
00:17:26,917 --> 00:17:27,499
And, um,

183
00:17:27,833 --> 00:17:35,441
What you do is actually developing your particular characteristic, your particular character.

184
00:17:36,342 --> 00:17:44,329
So it's a case of recognizing that the work you're doing is actually affecting your personality and your character.

185
00:17:44,891 --> 00:17:46,251
And that's why it's so important.

186
00:17:47,012 --> 00:17:50,997
And of course, there are particular types of trades that we don't want to get involved with.

187
00:17:51,798 --> 00:17:56,962
Trading in arms, in living beings, slavery and prostitution, meat trafficking.

188
00:17:57,365 --> 00:17:59,688
alcohol and poison.

189
00:17:59,748 --> 00:18:04,153
So those are the five ones that you try not to get involved with.

190
00:18:07,116 --> 00:18:23,777
So that shows you that there's a flow down from right understanding, right attitude, manifesting in the way we speak, in the way we behave and in our work.

191
00:18:24,144 --> 00:18:27,308
And the last three we'll come to at another time.

192
00:18:27,348 --> 00:18:34,477
They're basically to do, of course, with our meditation, both in the sitting, both in our sitting practice, but also in daily life.

193
00:18:34,517 --> 00:18:37,800
This mindfulness, affectionate mindfulness.

194
00:18:37,840 --> 00:18:53,038
The Buddha, you know, when we chant, when we read or chant the loving kindness discourse, when he talks about we should always live with this mindfulness, he's talking about a mindfulness which is imbued with a sense of kindness, a sense of goodwill.

195
00:18:53,608 --> 00:19:19,009
so the heart's always involved it's the same with your work i should have mentioned this um that there are these two uh these two qualities being attentive like you're you're attending to what you're doing but you have to give the heart a good reason so there's attention and care attention and care you can always bring care into anything sense of care and the important thing is that um

196
00:19:19,224 --> 00:19:22,888
all of these feedback, they feed back into themselves.

197
00:19:22,929 --> 00:19:33,018
Although we began with the importance of conceptual, of getting our concepts right, of understanding how we create suffering, et cetera, et cetera, of getting our attitudes right.

198
00:19:33,117 --> 00:19:34,279
And from then there's a flow.

199
00:19:34,579 --> 00:19:43,028
There's a feedback because as we behave, you know, coming from that position of wisdom, it feeds back into the wisdom.

200
00:19:43,067 --> 00:19:44,489
It supports the wisdom.

201
00:19:44,789 --> 00:19:47,071
And there's a desire to deepen that wisdom.

202
00:19:47,092 --> 00:19:48,252
There's a desire to

203
00:19:48,470 --> 00:19:53,395
to grow in those attitudes, love, compassion, joy, peace, and all that.

204
00:19:53,737 --> 00:19:55,739
They're known, remember, as illimitables.

205
00:19:56,460 --> 00:20:00,605
You can develop them without boundaries.

206
00:20:00,625 --> 00:20:01,846
They can just keep going.

207
00:20:02,307 --> 00:20:05,010
They can just be developed ad infinitum.

208
00:20:05,912 --> 00:20:09,096
There's no limit to how much we can develop mental states.

209
00:20:09,476 --> 00:20:12,180
And that's unfortunately true of evil states too.

210
00:20:12,299 --> 00:20:14,682
But here we're only concerned with what's good.

211
00:20:15,503 --> 00:20:17,987
So there's a sort of feedback loop in this.

212
00:20:18,220 --> 00:20:24,467
And the interesting one is between attitude and understanding.

213
00:20:24,926 --> 00:20:45,409
Because if we are drawn to compassionate action, to compassion which is driven by goodwill, action which is driven by generosity, by giving, remember that is constantly undermining the sense of this isolated me.

